	<text>
		<body>
				<p rend="align(center)">C O P Y</p>
				<p>Mr. Editor</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">In your <date>April</date> Number there appears a Communication from <placeName>California</placeName><lb/> over the signature of &#8220;<hi rend="underline"><persName>Theophilus</persName></hi>&#8221; relating to affairs in that distant part<lb/> of the Union&#44; which from his statements appear to be everything but what<lb/> they should be.  Among other things he avers that &#8220;<persName>Dr. Henry</persName> then refused to<lb/> make more proselytes&#8221; and then continues and says&#58; &#8220;Two&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;applied to the<lb/> Congregation Shearith Israel to be married to widows having no children&#44;<lb/> which <persName>Dr. Henry</persName> refused to do&#44; as he stated that the widows must have<lb/> and after continuing his bill of complaints in the same style&#44; finishes by evoking<lb/> your attention &#8220;to the right minded Israelites of <placeName>California</placeName>&#8221; which you in a<lb/> very kind and philosophic manner proceed so to do&#44; much no doubt to your own<lb/> satisfaction&#44; but perhaps without strict regard to the law which the question<lb/> raised.  Where do you find any such law as &#8220;The marriage of the two<lb/> certainly not in the Eben Haezer&#44; the place quoted by you in your <hi rend="underline">Note</hi>&#44;&#8221;<lb/> and Sir could you find it in any other place&#59; perhaps not.  And not content with<lb/> simply answering the question propounded&#44; you say &#8220;it would be the same if simple<lb/> Israelites.&#8221;  Now no such law as that can be found in any book of Standard<lb/> Authority among any Machtoh authors in the known world&#44; and why and for what<lb/> purpose do you answer &#8220;the right minded&#8221; people in that manner&#44; when you know&#44; if<lb/> you know anything about the matter at all&#44; that in the way the case was stated&#44;<lb/> there could be no objection to the marriage of the widows to the two or<lb/> to any other Israelites.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">&#8220;That a <persName>Cohen</persName> is prohibited form marrying a <hi rend="underline">Chabuzah</hi>&#8221; is stated by you&#44;<lb/> with reference to Iben Heazer V.1 is a most singular thing&#44; for the word<lb/> <hi rend="underline">Chabuzah</hi> is not mentioned in that place and as to the word&#44; perhaps you would<lb/> have done much better in your &#8220;Note&#8221; if you had told the &#8220;right minded&#8221; correctly<lb/> where it is to be found or what is the meaning of the word&#59; but <persname>Mr. Editor</persname> things<lb/> both in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> and <placeName>California</placeName> appear to be much out of place&#59; in one place<lb/> a <hi rend="underline">Dr</hi>. refused &#8220;to make any <hi rend="underline">more</hi> proselytes&#8221; while in the other an Editor refers<lb/> to places and laws not to be found&#44; and writes about a &#8220;Chabuzah&#8221; which puts all<lb/> his numerous readers on tiptoe of expectation hoping that in his next Number he<lb/> will tell them where the law is to be found which forbade a childless widow from<lb/> being married without and the meaning of the word chabuzah.</p>
			<p rend="indent(9)"><persName role="author">S. A.</persName></p>
				<p>Private</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Can you insert the above in <date>May</date> No.</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">Simon Ahaland&#44; M. D.</persName></p>
